data.content:
The best approach for your .NET 10 project is **`System.IO.Abstractions`** — a battle-tested NuGet package. No need to roll your own wrapper.

Looking at `ReportGenerator.cs`, you actually have **four** categories of statics:

| Category | Statics found | Recommended abstraction |
|---|---|---|
| File system | `File.WriteAllText`, `Directory.Exists`, `Directory.CreateDirectory` | `System.IO.Abstractions` (NuGet) |
| Time | `DateTime.UtcNow` (×2) | `TimeProvider` (built-in on .NET 10) |
| Environment | `GetEnvironmentVariable`, `MachineName` | Custom `IEnvironmentProvider` |
| Console | `Console.WriteLine` | Custom `IConsole` |

Here's how to adopt each:

---

### 1. File system — install `System.IO.Abstractions`

```sh
dotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions
```

Register in DI:
```csharp
builder.Services.AddSingleton<IFileSystem, FileSystem>();
```

Inject `IFileSystem` and use `fileSystem.File.WriteAllText(...)`, `fileSystem.Directory.Exists(...)`, etc.

In tests, install the helper package:
```sh
dotnet add <TestProject> package System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers
```
```csharp
var mockFs = new MockFileSystem();
mockFs.Directory.CreateDirectory("/tmp/reports");
var generator = new ReportGenerator(mockFs, ...);
// Assert against mockFs.File.ReadAllText(...)
```

---

### 2. Time — use built-in `TimeProvider`

Register in DI:
```csharp
builder.Services.AddSingleton(TimeProvider.System);
```

Replace `DateTime.UtcNow` with `timeProvider.GetUtcNow()`.

In tests:
```csharp
// dotnet add package Microsoft.Extensions.TimeProvider.Testing
var fakeTime = new FakeTimeProvider(new DateTimeOffset(2026, 1, 15, 0, 0, 0, TimeSpan.Zero));
var generator = new ReportGenerator(..., fakeTime);
```

---

### 3. Environment — minimal custom wrapper

Only wrap the two members you actually use:

```csharp
namespace NeedsWrappers;

public interface IEnvironmentProvider
{
    string? GetEnvironmentVariable(string variable);
    string MachineName { get; }
}

public sealed class EnvironmentProvider : IEnvironmentProvider
{
    public string? GetEnvironmentVariable(string variable)
        => Environment.GetEnvironmentVariable(variable);

    public string MachineName => Environment.MachineName;
}
```

Register: `builder.Services.AddSingleton<IEnvironmentProvider, EnvironmentProvider>();`

---

### 4. Refactored `ReportGenerator`

After all of these, the class becomes fully testable:

```csharp
public class ReportGenerator(
    IFileSystem fileSystem,
    TimeProvider timeProvider,
    IEnvironmentProvider environment)
{
    public string GenerateReport(string reportName)
    {
        var timestamp = timeProvider.GetUtcNow().ToString("yyyyMMdd_HHmmss");
        var outputDir = environment.GetEnvironmentVariable("REPORT_OUTPUT_DIR") ?? "/tmp/reports";

        if (!fileSystem.Directory.Exists(outputDir))
            fileSystem.Directory.CreateDirectory(outputDir);

        var reportPath = Path.Combine(outputDir, $"{reportName}_{timestamp}.txt");
        var content = $"Report: {reportName}\nGenerated: {timeProvider.GetUtcNow():O}\nMachine: {environment.MachineName}";

        fileSystem.File.WriteAllText(reportPath, content);
        return reportPath;
    }
}
```

Key principle: **only wrap statics you actually call** — don't speculatively wrap the entire `File` or `Environment` class. And prefer established packages (`System.IO.Abstractions`, `TimeProvider`) over hand-rolled wrappers.

